  "conditionals": 60,
  "created": "2025-10-14",
  "description": "The Unfolded Protein Response (UPR) in S. cerevisiae is an adaptive signaling pathway activated when misfolded proteins accumulate in the endoplasmic reticulum (ER). The pathway is mediated by Ire1, an ER-resident transmembrane kinase/endoribonuclease that senses ER stress through its luminal domain. Upon activation, Ire1 oligomerizes and splices HAC1 mRNA, producing the active transcription factor Hac1p. This induces expression of genes encoding ER chaperones, folding enzymes, lipid biosynthesis machinery, and ER-associated degradation (ERAD) components. The UPR increases ER capacity, enhances protein folding, and removes misfolded proteins. This flowchart illustrates the complete pathway from ER stress detection through Ire1 activation, HAC1 splicing, transcriptional response, and restoration of ER homeostasis.",
  "id": "yeast_unfolded_protein_response",
